{
  "texts": [
    "Additionally, 56 studies (23%) used hypothetical disease scenarios to demonstrate method applicability rather than investigating specific diseases.",
    "The recent surge in COVID-19 research has notably increased the volume of studies integrating AI with epidemiological models, with 217 (89%) of the included studies published between 2020 and 2023.",
    "Despite the increase in research study volume, the distribution of application areas for integrated models remained consistent over time (Fig. 2).",
    "We grouped the application areas into six primary categories (Fig. 2, Box 1, Supplementary Appendix 6): infectious disease forecasting (86 studies, 35%), model parameterization and calibration (77 studies, 31%), and disease intervention assessment and optimization (72 studies, 29%), followed by retrospective epidemic course analysis (16 studies, 7%), transmission inference (9 studies, 4%), and outbreak detection (7 studies, 3%).",
    "These categories are not mutually exclusive, indicating that a single integrated model can serve multiple application areas."
  ]
}